+// readWritePin implements read-after-write consistency. For an account that a
+// client has written, that account's reads must reflect at least the value the
+// client just wrote. Replicas lag behind the primary by an unbounded amount, so
+// a fixed time window is NOT sufficient to guarantee this: if replication lag
+// exceeds the window, reads fall back to the replica and observe the stale,
+// pre-write value.
+//
+// Instead we remember the exact balance produced by each account's most recent
+// write. A replica read is only trusted once it reflects that value; until then
+// reads are served from the primary, which is always authoritative. The pin is
+// cleared lazily once the replica has demonstrably caught up, so the primary is
+// not loaded forever.
+//
+// Each write also bumps a per-account sequence number; the recorded value is
+// keyed to a sequence so a concurrent later write is never overwritten by an
+// older one and so catch-up is evaluated against the latest write.
+type writeRecord struct {
+	seq     uint64
+	balance int64
+}
